    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-05-14T18:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-05-14T18:00:00-05:00" n="585"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d585">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">800.8820/1206: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Peru</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Norweb</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lima</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-05-14T18:00:00-05:00"
                            >May 14, 1943—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 10:21 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>697. Reference Embassy’s telegram No. 680, May 11, 7 p.m.<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d585fn3">Not printed.</note> and previous communications regarding
                    Peruvian ships in United States trade. The Finance Minister and the Embassy have
                    received notice from Grace and Company that the War Shipping Administration
                    insists the <hi rend="italic">Ucayali</hi> load cargo for New Orleans and gives
                    the impression the ship is more or less prohibited from going to San
                    Francisco.</p>
                <p>Our original agreement was the two ships would go to the West Coast. The Finance
                    Minister has assumed a responsible attitude but earnestly requests that the
                    ships be authorized as usual to load for San Francisco until full cargoes for
                    Peru are available there. Thereafter he will send them to New Orleans to
                    cooperate as closely as possible with the United States.</p>
                <p>This request seems reasonable and I wish to recommend it for the Department’s
                    most serious consideration.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Norweb</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
